        <body>
            <p>The <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dr. Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I am requested to Inform you <del>that</del> by
                        <persName>Wm.<add>?</add> Mayer</persName> &amp; <add>?</add><lb/> that a
                packet a <del>Packet</del> was sent to you yesterday by post without date or any
                prelim<lb/>inary remarks, the papers quite full and we were desirous to send them
                off without<lb/> delay. You will perceive that neither of us are
                    <sic>acustomed</sic> to write for the Occ<add>?</add>.<lb/> yet we have ventured
                to express our sentiments to the best of our ability, trusting<lb/> to your
                    <sic>judgement</sic> and the kindness of your correction (which you will be
                pleased to<lb/> make) which long experience has afforded you. <sic>be</sic> pleased
                to do us the justice to believe<lb/> that our motives are precisely as express in
                the communication sent you, and above all<lb/> the desire to cause yourself as an
                Editor and the public to be <sic>informd</sic> of the truth of<lb/> both sides of
                the question. We shall be pleased to learn from you that our<lb/> communications or
                any part of them will be serviceable for public information</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><sic>Doubless</sic> you are already informed that the <persName>Rev
                    J. Rosenfelt</persName> has tendered the<lb/> resignation of his ministry, which
                was accepted without any demur, report says<lb/> the health of his family, which
                does not agree with this climate in the cause slander says<lb/> there are other
                reasons, it is to be hoped that the community in general will not<lb/> suffer by
                this sudden <hi rend="underline">change</hi>— Our new <add>Hebrew</add> is erected
                and under a stated<lb/> roof, it is a beautiful structure, and has an imposing
                appearance, if its members<lb/> do not add <sic>concequence</sic> to it, the
                Building certainly <hi rend="underline">has</hi> given great
                <sic>concequence</sic><lb/> to them, the commodious vist<add>?</add> room on the
                ground floor which is 33 by nearly 80<lb/> &amp; 15 high is nearly finished it is
                intended to have divine service in that room on<lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add> It is expected to consecrate the <add>Hebrew</add> on the coming
                    <add>Hebrew</add>. The Ladies<lb/> have subscribed several Hundreds of Dollars
                for <add>Hebrew</add> &amp; stairs carpet for the alter &amp; &amp;<lb/> A society
                which has been named <add>Hebrew</add> has been organized for the<lb/> purpose of
                    <sic>ministring</sic> to the wants of the sick the Dying &amp; the dead. They
                number<lb/> already of 55 persons a <add>Hebrew</add>—and <add>Hebrew</add> is
                attached to the society. The first con<add>?</add><lb/> for the benefit of our
                Jewish Hospital on Western Row, comes off this Eveng at the<lb/> Melodian, from the
                vast am't of tickets already sold it is expected the Hall will be<lb/>
                <sic>filld</sic> to an overflow. I am desired by <persName>Mr. Mayer</persName> to
                say that he will shortly<lb/> be in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> when he will
                do himself the honor of calling with you<lb/> please to accept our respects and best
                wishes</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I am</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)"> your. mo obj.</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <persName role="author">Samuel Bruel</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <placeName>Cincin</placeName>
            </p>
